      en: {
        metaTitle: "Taxi Lille → Bruges | Fixed price from €130 | TaxiNeo",
        metaDescription: "Taxi Lille → Bruges. 100 km, 1h15, from €130. Venice of the North, canals, chocolate. Book 24/7.",
        heroTitle: "Taxi Lille → Bruges",
        heroSubtitle: "Your Lille → Bruges transfer at €130 — €165. 100 km via Belgium.",
        description: "Bruges, the Venice of the North with its canals and UNESCO medieval centre, is 1h15 from Lille by taxi.",
        routeDescription: "The route takes the A22 to Belgium, then the E40 towards Bruges via Kortrijk.",
        introduction: "Bruges is one of Europe's most beautiful cities, often called the Venice of the North for its romantic canals, stone bridges and preserved medieval façades. The historic centre, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, is an intact architectural gem from the Middle Ages: the Belfry on the Market Square (83 metres, 366 steps), the Basilica of the Holy Blood, the Church of Our Lady housing Michelangelo's Madonna, the Beguinage (Begijnhof) with its daffodil garden, and canals lined with stepped-gable houses. Bruges is also the capital of Belgian chocolate, with over 50 artisan chocolatiers in the centre, and of Flemish lace. Belgian beer is ubiquitous, notably the Brugse Zot brewed at De Halve Maan, the only active brewery in the historic centre. From Lille, Bruges is a perfect day trip by taxi: the journey is short, the border crossing invisible (Schengen area), and the return at day's end is worry-free with no connections or last trains. A taxi is ideal because trains from Lille to Bruges require a change at Kortrijk, and parking in central Bruges is very expensive and limited.",
        itineraire: "Your driver leaves Lille via the A22 towards Belgium. The Franco-Belgian border crossing is imperceptible — just a sign marking entry into Belgium. You first cross Mouscron (a French-speaking Belgian town), then join the E17 motorway towards Kortrijk. At Kortrijk, a historic city of the Battle of the Golden Spurs (1302), you branch onto the E40 towards Ostend and Bruges. The E40 crosses West Flanders, a fertile agricultural plain with flax fields, Flemish farms and windmills. Arrival in Bruges is via the Brugge Centrum exit, and your driver drops you as close to the historic centre as possible — ideally at Bruges station or the 't Zand car park, from where the pedestrian centre is a 5-minute walk. Tolls are minimal (about €3 on the French side); Belgian motorways are toll-free. The journey takes 1h15 normally and can reach 1h40 on tourist weekends.",
        conseils: "Bruges is very touristy — visit preferably on weekdays or off-season (November-March, except Christmas) to avoid crowds. The centre is entirely pedestrian and compact: everything can be visited on foot in a day. The canal boat tour (€8, 30 min) is unmissable. For chocolate, The Chocolate Line (Dominique Persoone) and Dumon are the most reputed artisans. Brugse Zot is sampled at De Halve Maan brewery (tour + tasting: €12). Bruges waffles (thin butter wafers) differ from Brussels waffles — try both! Beware of prices: Bruges is expensive for Belgium. Favour restaurants on side streets rather than the Market Square. The Groeninge Museum (Flemish painting, Van Eyck, Memling) deserves 1h30. The Procession of the Holy Blood (May, Ascension) is a unique Bruges event. Our taxi waits during your visit if you choose the hourly hire option.",
        comparaisonTransport: "The train Lille — Bruges requires a change at Kortrijk, costs €15-25 and takes 1h30 to 2h depending on connection. Frequency is decent (hourly) but the change is inconvenient with luggage. FlixBus offers tickets from €10 but takes 2h30. By car, expect €12 in fuel with no toll (Belgian side). The TaxiNeo taxi at €130 — €165 provides seamless door-to-door service with no border hassle or connections. For 3-4 passengers, the cost (€33-55 per person) is very competitive against the train. And crucially, the taxi saves you searching for parking in Bruges (€25-35/day when available).",
        faq: [
          { question: "Do I need a passport to go to Bruges?", answer: "No, Belgium is part of the Schengen area. A French ID card is sufficient. There are no border controls." },
          { question: "Can the taxi enter central Bruges?", answer: "The historic centre is pedestrianised, but your driver drops you as close as possible: 't Zand car park, Bruges station or Minnewater, 2-5 min walk from the centre." },
          { question: "Can I visit Bruges and Ghent in one day?", answer: "Feasible but ambitious. Bruges in the morning (4h), Ghent in the afternoon (3h), return to Lille in the evening. With our hourly hire, the driver handles the Bruges → Ghent transfers (50 km, 45 min)." },
          { question: "Does the taxi accept euros in Belgium?", answer: "The TaxiNeo fare is set in euros and paid at booking (card, transfer). You pay nothing to the driver — Belgium uses the euro, like France." },
          { question: "What is the best season to visit Bruges?", answer: "Spring (April-May) for the Beguinage daffodils. Summer is very busy. Autumn is pleasant and less touristy. The Christmas Market (late Nov-Dec) is magnificent but very popular." }
        ],
      },
